This paper deals with wireless device-to-device (D2D) networks and their throughput-outage tradeoff. It focuses on the impact of caching on the network performance, which is a topic that falls under the information theory (cs.IT) and networking and internet architecture (cs.NI) categories. The paper also uses the Gupta and Kumar protocol model, which is a well-known model in the field of wireless networks, and thus it could be classified under the systems and control (cs.SI) category. Additionally, the paper discusses the scalability of the D2D caching network, which could be relevant to the distributed, parallel, and cluster computing (cs.DC) category. Finally, the paper presents a mathematical analysis of the system, which could be related to the machine learning (cs.LG) category.
